{"id":601,"date":"2010-10-15T14:05:53","date_gmt":"2010-10-15T14:05:53","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/joind.co.uk\/?p=601"},"modified":"2023-04-26T09:59:45","modified_gmt":"2023-04-26T09:59:45","slug":"why-blog","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/why-blog\/","title":{"rendered":"The number one reason why I blog"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><strong>PLEASURE<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>That&#8217;s it, I&#8217;ve said it.<\/p>\n<p>I was leading a workshop for Birmingham Book Festival last weekend called Finding Your Blogging Voice. One of the first things we did was brainstorm our reasons for blogging. Between us we said:<!--more--><\/p>\n<ul style=\"margin-bottom: 15px;\">\n<li>to have a voice<\/li>\n<li>to showcase work<\/li>\n<li>to create an archive of material<\/li>\n<li>to explain a business<\/li>\n<li>to connect with people<\/li>\n<li>to improve SEO.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>I was leading the workshop and so I forgot to say that, though I do indeed get all those benefits from blogging, my number one reason for going tap, tap, tap is because I enjoy it.<\/p>\n<p>There are all sorts of different pleasures, of course.<\/p>\n<h3>Blogging isn&#8217;t like sex<\/h3>\n<p>The pleasure of blogging isn&#8217;t like that of sex or swimming or lying on the sofa with a glass of wine. It&#8217;s\u00a0 more like the pleasure of making a photo album &#8211; but using word-pictures rather than images.<\/p>\n<p>And, <a href=\"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/virginia-woolf\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">as I said when I created this website,<\/a> it&#8217;s like the pleasure of having my own room and getting it just how I want &#8211; my own little bit of cyberpace where I can play and muse and hang out with my friends.<\/p>\n<p>In her seminal post <a href=\"http:\/\/www.oreillynet.com\/pub\/a\/javascript\/2002\/06\/13\/megnut.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">What We&#8217;re Doing When We Blog,<\/a> Meg Hourian talks about the anatomy of a post and the communication evolution etc.\u00a0 It&#8217;s all good stuff.<\/p>\n<p>But she doesn&#8217;t say: &#8220;Having fun.&#8221;\u00a0 That&#8217;s what I&#8217;m doing when I blog and the day it stops being enjoyable, is the day I&#8217;ll stop blogging.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>PLEASURE. That&#8217;s it, I&#8217;ve said it. I was leading a workshop for Birmingham Book Festival last weekend called Finding Your Blogging Voice. One of the first things we did was brainstorm our reasons for blogging. Between us we said:<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":2636,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[4,12],"tags":[32,59,141,156,177,205],"class_list":["post-601","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-digital","category-writing","tag-blog","tag-cyber-room","tag-new-media","tag-pleasure","tag-seo","tag-writing"],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/601"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=601"}],"version-history":[{"count":1,"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/601\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":7057,"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/601\/revisions\/7057"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/2636"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=601"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=601"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/j